                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">1. <u>Be an Active Listener: 
                            
                        </u>
                        </H3>
                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            One can be a great orator only when one is an excellent listener. Being an active listener and paying attention to what other people say and how they deliver their messages will help you improve your communication skills immensely. Even during school discussions and group debates, ensure that you are not only focused on making your point heard but also listen to and acknowledge what the other person has to say.  
                        </p>
                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">2. <u>Practice Communicating in Front of the Mirror:
                        </u>
                        </H3>
                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Start honing your communication skills by practising a few lines in front of the mirror. Be it a few lines of a casual conversation or a formal speech; you can speak it as eloquently as possible while facing a mirror. Monitor yourself while you talk. This trick would help you easily detect the errors you make while speaking and understand the aspects you need to improve while communicating. 

                        </p>
                   
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="Girl looking into mirror and saying I can do it" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Improve%20Your%20Communication%20Skills%3F%2F17888008.jpg?alt=media&token=7ddaad07-47a9-41fd-beff-81de0a35d0ca" >
                            </div>
                            </div> 

                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">3. <u>Keep a Few Points Ready:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                When you need to address an audience during formal situations, for example, while giving class presentations, keep a small note with a few important points with you. You can write down the essential aspects you wish to touch upon while speaking. This will give you a considerable amount of confidence since you won’t have to rely solely on memory and can catch a quick glimpse of a few points from your note in case you forget them while communicating. 
                            </p>
                           
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">4. <u>Start with Little Content:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                In the initial stages of practice, start with practising small bits of content. For example, start with rehearsing a paragraph (of casual conversational lines or academic content). You can gradually build your capacity by increasing the quantity of the content bit by bit. Once you feel comfortable speaking one para confidently, try including a couple more paras while practising and make progress.
                            </p>
                            <div class="row" >
                                <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                    <img alt="student holding pencil" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Improve%20Your%20Communication%20Skills%3F%2F20943483.jpg?alt=media&token=791ebd7a-de27-41da-81d2-2e9981d4fbed" >
                                </div>
                                </div>
  <br>
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">5. <u>Cover a Wide Range of Topics:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                While practising and honing your communication skills, try covering a wide range of topics to communicate on. You start with more simple and casual topics like discussing your hobbies and passions and build your way through more complex topics like social inequality and injustices. This would help you ensure that you gradually become comfortable conversing on a wide range of topics rather than being restricted to a few.  
  </p>

                                <H3 style=" font-style: underline">6. <u>Gradually Increase the Size of Your Audience:
                                </u>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    Once you feel confident conversing alone in front of the mirror, you can start talking in front of people. You can start with practising little speeches or lines of conversation with your parents or close friends. After this stage, you can proceed with interacting in front of a larger audience, for example, in front of your classmates. This would slowly build your confidence and give you the courage to communicate with a larger set of people.
                                </p>
                                <div class="row" >
                                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                        <img alt="Communication is key poster" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Improve%20Your%20Communication%20Skills%3F%2FWavy_Tech-15_Single-04.jpg?alt=media&token=8df1dbe2-a8ea-4c50-96d0-80f72745bf75" >
                                    </div>
                                    </div>
                                <H3 style=" font-style: underline">7. <u>Be Mindful of Your Gestures and Body Language:
                                </u>
                                
      <br>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    Maintaining eye contact can be intimidating initially; however, looking into people’s eyes while communicating draws their interest towards your speech and gives out an air of confidence. You can use hand gestures freely while communicating. Since gestures often accompany conversation naturally, they will help you feel more comfortable and at ease while talking. Maintain a good upright posture and avoid slouching since good body language is essential in good communication.         </p>
                                
                                </p>
                               
                                    <H3 style=" font-style: underline">8. <u>Hone your Fluency and Voice Modulation:
                                </u>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    Conversing fluently without stammering and fumbling ensures that you keep the flow of your conversation going. In case you forget a point while speaking, use gap-filling statements such as:
  </p><ul style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
    <li>●	“So, the point I was trying to arrive at is….”</li>
    <li>●	“I would like to further mention that….”</li>
    <li>●	“On that note, this is what I am trying to highlight….”</li>
        </ul>
  <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
    These statements will give you more time to recollect your point. The more you practice, the more fluent you become while conversing. Voice modulation is essential while communicating with a larger audience. You can speak in a lower voice while communicating with a smaller set of people. However, while addressing a large audience, ensure that you raise your pitch enough to be audible to the audience. This would enable clear and effective communication. 
</p>
